    "summary": "The Late Western Zhou period (c. 900–771 BC) was the declining phase of the Western Zhou dynasty, marked by weakening royal authority, increasing power of feudal lords, and the gradual erosion of the ritual and political order that the early Zhou kings had established. The Zhou kings had legitimized their rule through the doctrine of the 'Mandate of Heaven' (Tianming) — the idea that Heaven grants authority to a virtuous ruler and withdraws it from a corrupt one. The Zhou had used this doctrine to justify their overthrow of the Shang dynasty; now it was being implicitly used against them.\n\nLate Western Zhou bronze inscriptions document a court struggling with border pressures (from the Xianyun nomads in the north), internal conflicts, and the challenges of maintaining control over an expanding feudal system. The reign of King You (781–771 BC) ended catastrophically: according to tradition, his doting on the concubine Bao Si led him to light the beacon fires (the warning system for a nomadic attack) as a prank, so that when a real attack came, the feudal lords did not respond. The Quanrong nomads sacked the capital Hao in 771 BC (see [[event:2002|Sack of Haojing]]), forcing the Zhou court eastward and ending the Western Zhou period. Whether or not the legend is accurate, the political reality was a royal court that had lost the confidence of its feudal nobility.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_Zhou",
